**1. Serialization Format**

The graph is serialized as JSON-LD. JSON-LD is the canonical interchange
format. It is importable into Neo4j via the provided import scripts and
compatible with RDF triple stores via standard JSON-LD processing.

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **PORTABILITY CLAIM**                                                 |
|                                                                       |
| The graph is serialized as JSON-LD with deterministic field mappings. |
| A Neo4j import script is provided that handles the transformation    |
| from JSON-LD to Neo4j property graph format. RDF import requires     |
| standard JSON-LD framing and expansion, handled by any conformant    |
| JSON-LD processor.                                                    |
|                                                                       |
| The transformation is provided and versioned alongside the graph.    |
| Contributors do not need to write transformation code.               |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**1.1 File structure**

> * /data/conlaw_graph_v02.json --- combined graph, all slices, all
> fixes applied. This is the authoritative source for Neo4j import.
>
> * /validate.py --- full validator, run before every import
>
> * /neo4j_import.py --- Neo4j import pipeline v0.4
>
> * /courtlistener_pipeline_v3.py --- CourtListener citation pipeline

**1.2 JSON-LD top-level structure**

  {
    "meta": {
      "version": "0.5",
      "schema_version": "0.5",
      "slices": [...],
      "node_count": 244,
      "edge_count": 522,
      "schema_issue_count": 0
    },
    "nodes": {
      "areas": [...],
      "doctrines": [...],
      "doctrinal_tests": [...],
      "cases": [...],
      "constitutional_provisions": [...]
    },
    "edges": [...]
  }

