**2. Neo4j Import**

**2.1 Node type to Neo4j label mapping**

  -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **JSON-LD @type**             **Neo4j Label**            **Secondary Label**
  ----------------------------- -------------------------- ----------------------------------
  Area                          :Area                      :TaxonomyNode

  Doctrine                      :Doctrine                  :TaxonomyNode

  DoctrinalTest                 :DoctrinalTest             :TaxonomyNode

  Case                          :Case                      :AuthorityNode

  ConstitutionalProvision       :ConstitutionalProvision   :AuthorityNode
  -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

**2.2 Edge type to Neo4j relationship mapping**

All JSON-LD edge_type values map directly to Neo4j relationship types
with the same name. Edge attributes map to Neo4j relationship properties.
PRECONDITION_TO maps to the :PRECONDITION_TO relationship type.

**2.3 Neo4j connection details (AuraDB)**

  URI:       neo4j+s://779dfe5d.databases.neo4j.io
  Username:  779dfe5d
  Database:  779dfe5d
  Password:  [in environment / not committed to version control]

Note: AuraDB Free uses the instance ID as both username and database
name --- not the default "neo4j". The URI scheme is neo4j+s:// (not
bolt+s://).

MCP server config for Claude Desktop (requires uvx):
  mcp-neo4j-cypher with full path to uvx, Neo4j URI, and SSL cert path.

**2.4 Import pipeline usage**

  # Standard import with wipe
  echo "yes" | python3 neo4j_import.py \
    --uri "neo4j+s://779dfe5d.databases.neo4j.io" \
    --user 779dfe5d \
    --password "[password]" \
    --file conlaw_graph_v02.json \
    --wipe

  # Validate before import
  python3 validate.py --file conlaw_graph_v02.json

The import pipeline runs canonical query tests (QT-1 through QT-6) after
every import to verify graph integrity.

**2.5 Canonical query tests**

These six queries run automatically after every Neo4j import. All six
must return results to pass.

QT-1: What tests currently govern commercial speech?
  MATCH (a:Area {id: 'commercial_speech'})-[:GOVERNED_BY]->(t:DoctrinalTest)
  WHERE t.status = 'active'
  RETURN t.id as test_id, t.label as test_label, t.status as status

QT-2: What cases touch the Brandenburg incitement test?
  MATCH (c:Case)-[r:ESTABLISHES|MODIFIES|APPLIES]->(t:DoctrinalTest {id: 'brandenburg_test'})
  RETURN c.short_name as case_name, c.decided_date as date,
         type(r) as relationship, r.direction as direction
  ORDER BY c.decided_date

QT-3: Full doctrinal lineage of the Brandenburg test
  MATCH (source:Case)-[ip:INTELLECTUALLY_PRECEDES]->(target:Case)
        -[:ESTABLISHES]->(t:DoctrinalTest {id: 'brandenburg_test'})
  RETURN source.short_name as intellectual_source,
         source.decided_date as source_date,
         target.short_name as establishing_case,
         target.decided_date as established_date

QT-4: Taxonomy path from commercial speech to root
  MATCH path = (a:Area {id: 'commercial_speech'})-[:CHILD_OF*]->(root:Area)
  WHERE NOT (root)-[:CHILD_OF]->()
  RETURN [n IN nodes(path) | n.label] as taxonomy_path

QT-5: All overruled cases with their overruling cases
  MATCH (b:Case)-[r:OVERRULES]->(a:Case)
  RETURN b.short_name as overruling, b.decided_date as overruling_date,
         a.short_name as overruled, a.decided_date as overruled_date,
         r.overrule_type as type
  ORDER BY b.decided_date

QT-6: All RELATED_TO connections across doctrinal areas
  MATCH (a1:Area)-[:RELATED_TO]-(a2:Area)
  WHERE id(a1) < id(a2)
  RETURN a1.label as area1, a2.label as area2
  ORDER BY a1.label

**3. CourtListener Integration**

**3.1 What CourtListener provides**

> * Full opinion text for all federal decisions
>
> * Citation metadata (party names, court, date, docket number)
>
> * Citation network (what cases cite this case)
>
> * CourtListener cluster ID --- the stable identifier for linking

**3.2 Data tier model**

Tier 1 (curated): Hand-modeled nodes at casebook depth. Holdings, votes,
authors, opinion significance, and all edges are human-reviewed. These
are the nodes that form the doctrinal spine.

Tier 2 (auto_imported / inferred): Cases identified by citation depth
from CourtListener. Minimum metadata only. Live CourtListener queries
at research time augment these with full opinion text. These nodes are
not added to the main graph by default --- they are surfaced via live
API queries using the courtlistener_id field on Tier 1 nodes as the
lookup hook.

Tier 1 is the graph. Tier 2 is the citation network around the graph.

**3.3 CourtListener pipeline v3**

The pipeline is operational at courtlistener_pipeline_v3.py.
Three-strategy architecture:

  Strategy 1 (post-2000): Direct cluster search by case name + year.
  Strategy 2 (pre-2000, precise): OpenSearch with party name filters.
  Strategy 3 (pre-2000, fallback): Cluster enumeration with citation depth.

Flags:
  --min-depth N   Minimum citation depth to include a case (default: 2)
  --max-results N Maximum results per case (default: 20)
  --case-ids      Comma-separated list of case IDs to process

Primary use: populate courtlistener_id on existing Tier 1 Case nodes.
Secondary use: identify high-citation-depth cases that may warrant
promotion to Tier 1 (human review required).

**3.4 Integration status**

courtlistener_id is populated for the 13 commercial speech cases added
in CourtListener batch 1. Approximately 230 curated Case nodes still
need courtlistener_id populated.

**4. Merge Pipeline**

**4.1 Merge steps**

> * 1. Validate current combined graph (validate.py)
> * 2. Write new nodes and edges to combined graph file
> * 3. Update meta.node_count, meta.edge_count
> * 4. Validate merged graph
> * 5. If validation passes: import to Neo4j (neo4j_import.py --wipe)
> * 6. Verify QT-1 through QT-6 pass
> * 7. Copy to /mnt/user-data/outputs/ and commit to GitHub

**4.2 Current graph status**

  Combined graph: conlaw_graph_v02.json
  Nodes: 244
  Edges: 522
  Validation errors: 0
  Slices: First Amendment (complete, casebook depth + CourtListener batch 1)
          Equal Protection (complete, casebook depth, 2 QC passes)

**5. Agent Pipeline Architecture** [Planned --- not yet built]

The agent pipeline automates graph expansion for new doctrinal areas.
It is model-agnostic and designed to run on LangGraph / Vertex AI.

**5.1 Pipeline components**

Graph Builder (Generator): Takes a prompt (e.g., "Map the substantive
due process doctrine") and generates draft JSON nodes and edges, strictly
adhering to the v0.5 schema. Recommended model: Gemini 1.5 Pro (large
context window for casebook ingestion).

QA: Semantic / Schema (Pydantic + validate.py): Verifies the draft JSON
against v0.5 schema constraints. This is largely the existing validator
plus Pydantic model enforcement. No LLM required.

QA: Factual / Citation (CourtListener): Cross-references generated Case
nodes against CourtListener API. Verifies case names, citations, dates,
vote counts, and majority authors. Flags hallucinated cases.

QA: Legal Pressure Test (LLM-as-Judge): Spins up draft JSON into an
ephemeral NetworkX sandbox. Generates hypothetical legal scenarios,
executes them against the temporary graph, and evaluates whether the
traversal paths match doctrinal reality. Recommended model: Claude
(legal reasoning quality for pressure testing).

Orchestrator: Routes output between components. If any QA agent fails,
kicks draft back to Graph Builder with specific error logs for revision.
If all three QA agents pass, flags for human review.

Human Review: Diff of approved JSON against current graph. Human
confirms before merge to Neo4j Production.

**5.2 Schema requirement**

The Graph Builder must be given the current version of all four spec
documents as its primary constraints. Do not build the agent pipeline
against a stale schema version. The v0.5 spec documents are the minimum
acceptable input.

**5.3 Build order**

Do not build the agent pipeline until:
  1. v0.5 schema spec is complete and committed (this document)
  2. At least two doctrinal branches validated manually (done: 1A + EP)
  3. Validator updated to enforce all v0.5 rules
  4. PRECONDITION_TO edge type implemented in validator

